The description: Chart 1 stacked bars showing % decline in mobility split into lockdown stringency and voluntary social distancing, across categories. Potential issues: using stacked bar to compare contributions may be okay. But "percentage decline in mobility" likely a relative measure; could be misleading if axis not starting at zero? Stacked bars often start at zero but not necessarily. Could be "truncated axis" if y-axis doesn't start at zero, exaggerating differences. Not mentioned.

Chart 2: cumulative cases per thousand vs days since first case, two lines for countries that tightened lockdowns with high vs low cases, shaded interquartile ranges. Potential issues: grouping countries by when they tightened lockdowns may be cherry-picking; also causal inference: claiming early lockdowns cause lower cases, but correlation not causation. Could be "Causal inference" error. Also could be "Cherry-picking" if only showing certain countries, not all.

Also "Issues with data validity": no mention of confounders, testing rates, etc. Might be "Failure to account for statistical nuance": not accounting for baseline differences.

Thus likely misleading due to causal inference and cherry-picking.

Intentional? Possibly, as the chart appears to support policy argument. Could be intentional persuasion.
